\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Entrepreneurship,
 often associated with innovation and firm growth,
 is a cornerstone of economic development.
 Yet,
 this image predominantly applies to a fraction of business owners who embark on such ventures from the start.
 A significant number of entrepreneurs are driven by necessity—
they establish businesses when there are no other employment options available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While entrepreneurs focused on innovation and growth undoubtedly contribute positively to the economy,
 the impact of necessity entrepreneurship is more nuanced.
 Although it can serve as a safety net during periods of unemployment,
 it might also lead to misallocation of talent,
 as those who start businesses out of necessity might be more productive as employees within an existing firm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Globally,
 there is a negative correlation between entrepreneurship and economic development.
 This pattern is largely driven by low-income countries,
 where a higher share of entrepreneurs report starting firms out of necessity.
 When considering only those who report starting a business for opportunistic reasons,
 the relationship between entrepreneurship and economic development becomes positive (Chivers,
 2017).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Defining opportunity-driven versus necessity-driven entrepreneurship,
 however,
 presents several challenges.
 The Global Entrepreneurship Monitor (GEM) provides nationally representative survey data and classifies entrepreneurs using the question:
 “Are you involved in this start-up to take advantage of a business opportunity or because you have no better choices for work?” Naturally,
 relying on self-reported data introduces potential measurement error.
 Fairlie and Fossen (2019) propose an empirical approach in which opportunity-driven entrepreneurs are defined as individuals who were previously employed,
 while necessity entrepreneurs were previously unemployed.
 Although this definition is empirically tractable,
 it cannot fully capture the underlying motivation:
 for example,
 someone may leave a job to pursue a promising business idea and thus appear as a “necessity” entrepreneur,
 or someone employed may start a firm to hedge against potential job loss.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper,
 we provide a theoretical definition of entrepreneurship based on agents’ optimal occupational choices,
 taking into account their managerial talent,
 employment status,
 education level and wealth(?) We define opportunity-driven entrepreneurs as those who would choose self-employment regardless of their employment circumstances,
 and necessity entrepreneurs as those who would not have chosen entrepreneurship if other employment options were available.
 This conceptualization allows us to frame necessity entrepreneurship as a potential form of misallocation,
 where individuals engage in self-employment not because it is their most productive option,
 but because external constraints limit their alternatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Model:
 Economic Environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a Lucas (1978) span of control model,
 where individuals differ in the level of human capital,
 
\begin_inset Formula $h.$
\end_inset

 As in Gomez and Kuhen (2017),
 individuals are educated to either the primary 
\begin_inset Formula $(P)$
\end_inset

,
 secondary 
\begin_inset Formula $(S)$
\end_inset

 or tertiary level 
\begin_inset Formula $(T)$
\end_inset

.
 The level of education means that a tertiary educated individuals have a higher draw of human capital,
 on average,
 than secondary educated individuals,
 who in turn have a higher draw on average than primary educated individuals.
 This human capital draw is positively correlated with managerial ability 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as well as labor productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the start of the period agents enter as either unemployed 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=0)$
\end_inset

,
 employed 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=1)$
\end_inset

,
 or an entrepreneur 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=2)$
\end_inset

.
 Individuals face a choice of whether to become an entrepreneur,
 to continue working or to search for work.
 However,
 the value of employment is different depending on whether an agent enters the period as employed 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=1)$
\end_inset

 or not.
 Although there is a risk that an employee may become separated from a firm with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

,
 this is less risky than searching for work which has a 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\theta)$
\end_inset

 probability of obtaining employment.
 Consequently,
 the expected value of employment is higher for those already in employment than those who are not.
 Additionally,
 the probability of separation is lower for individuals with higher levels of human capital and they are able to command a higher wage due to higher levels of productivity.
 So the value of employment,
 holding other things equal,
 is higher for those with higher human capital as well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The innovation of this model is that the entrepreneurial decision results in two types of entrepreneurs emerge,
 opportunity-based entrepreneurs and necessity-based entrepreneurs.
 We define opportunity-based entrepreneurs are those whose value of entrepreneurship is higher,
 even if they had employment.
 Necessity-based entrepreneurs are those who would not have become entrepreneurs,
 if they had employment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Timing:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of events can be summarized below.
 Occupational choice happens at the start of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t.$
\end_inset

 Those choosing to become entrepreneurs run projects and hire workers on on rolling contracts (i.e.
 contracts,
 will be reassessed each period).
 Those who were previously employed within a project can decide to carry on working but carry a risk of separation with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 If separation occurs these workers will claim unemployed benefits and be unable to look for work until the following period.
 After separation occurs,
 vacancies are posted and who were unemployed in the previous period are matched with firms.
 Those that are successful and match with with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\theta)$
\end_inset

 go on to earn a wage.
 Whereas those that are unsuccessful will claim unemployment benefits and be unable to search again until the following period.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the search and matching literature there is no wage bargaining between workers and the firm at the end of matching.
 Instead the wage pins down the occupational choice decision which determines those wanting to become entrepreneurs and those who will search for work.
 Crucially,
 the worker only finds out whether they enter production and earn a wage after their occupational choice decision.
 
\end_layout

