 The upshot of this is that when markets are tight,
 the size of the desired firm size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 decreases ex ante ,
 as the cost of replacing workers is high and so entrepeneurs would prefer to run smaller firms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To avoid issues of directed search,
 we assume that employees are randomly matched with firms (as in Chivers et al.,
 2015) and each firm employees a distribution of workers accross the human capital spectrum such that each firm employs the market averaege.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimal behavior and equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 agents are distinguished by 
\begin_inset Formula $(h,a,x,i,z)$
\end_inset

.
 The timing of the economy is given as follows.
 
\end_layout

